	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>London</placeName>. <date>Jany. 24<hi rend="sup">Th</hi> 5614&#47;1854</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I have long proposed to have this pleasure if<lb/> only to inform you of <persName>Mrs. Nathan</persName> and myself not having forgotten you&#44; but apart from<lb/> the disarrangement which moving from one country to another occasions&#44; and the unfixed<lb/> habits it creates&#44; my poor wife has&#44; I regret to say been an invalid for the last 11 weeks.<lb/>  Her sufferings have been so severe&#44; as to have debarred me from communicating with<lb/> even an old friend like you.  I wished particularly to send you my address&#44; having<lb/> noticed in the slip round the Occident directed to me&#44; and for which thoughtful<lb/> act I kindly thank you&#44; your request to <persName>Mrs Joel</persName> to ascertain my whereabouts<lb/> <persName>Mrs. N.</persName> is I am happy to say mending&#44; tho&#39; very slowly.  Her situation in a city<lb/> where friends are separated by such great distances as to render a friendly visit<lb/> a toil&#44; has confined me to the house to relieve the tediousness of her solitude&#44; so that<lb/> I know little or nothing of Jewish affairs&#44; and the pending controversy between<lb/> the Board of deputies and the country congregations&#44; the only subject I suppose<lb/> about which you care to know I have met with <persName>Dr. Adler</persName> twice&#44; and in my<lb/> next will offer a few observations respecting him and the Jews generally.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It was my intention to visit <placeName>America</placeName> on my way to <placeName>Europe</placeName>&#44; but<lb/> the steamers would have taken us first to <placeName>Aspinwall</placeName>&#44; and I feared going<lb/> to the <placeName>Isthmus</placeName> even for a few days after the experience I had of it last<lb/> <date>January</date>.  I wished especially to see <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> once more for the sake<lb/> of seeing old friends again&#44; and ascertaining also whether it would have<lb/> suited us to live there.  &#8220;Man denkt aber Gott lenkt.&#8221;   Convey however to our numerous<lb/> friends there our warmest remembrances&#44; and our hopes that we may yet<lb/> meet again in this life.  How is your Bible getting on&#63;  When will it be ready&#63;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Did the translation I lent you of the Book of <persName>Job</persName> prove of any service&#44; in opening<lb/> up new readings &#38;c&#63;  What do you think of <persName>Gutheim&#39;s</persName> accepting my late situation<lb/> after resigning his former one on the plea of intention of quitting the ministry alto&#45;<lb/>gether&#63;  Rather strange the whole proceeding.  God be with you is the united<lb/> wish of <persName>Mrs. N</persName> and myself&#44; and hoping this will meet you and all friends<lb/> in good health</p>   
			<p rend="indent(9)">I am</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)">Your&#39;s as of old</p>
			<p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">M N Nathan</persName></p>
				<p>Direct to me care of <persName>Messrs Carvalho &#38; Delgado</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>8 &#189; Cross St.</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><placeName>Finsbury</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><placeName>London</placeName>.</p>
		</body>
